Introduction¶

The datasets selected for this report are from the Education and Population categories along with GDP and Life expectancy from Gapminder.org. These datasets contain annual data for countries as a whole and vary in dimension, source and provider. The number of years collected, as well as the number of countries and completeness of data varies greatly. It may be organizational, political and/or financial resources that make the collection of data possible, so it is likely that the results tend to favour stronger more affluent countries. The focus of this investigation is to see whether schooling for women has changed over time and how years in school for women relates to Urban population, Life expectancy and GDP per capita.

The Gapminder.org's Indicator datasets chosen for this investigation are (with Data provider):

  • Mean years in school (men 25 to 34 years) | IHME (Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation)
  • Mean years in school (women 25 to 34 years) | IHME
  • GDP/capita (US$, inflation-adjusted) | World Bank
  • Life expectancy (years) | Various sources
  • Urban population (% of total) | World Bank

The investigation attempts to answer these questions:

  1. How have Mean years in school for women changed over time?
  2. How does Mean years in school for women compare to that for men?
  3. What region has seen Mean years in school for women increase the most?
  4. Which countries have seen the greatest increase in Mean years in school for women?
  5. What variables are associated with the countries that have seen the greatest increase in Mean years in school for women?
  6. How does Mean years in school for women relate to Life expectancy?

To answer the questions the wider region as well as country levels was considered, using region categories taken from Data Geographies - v1 - by Gapminder.xlsx, an Excel file that Gapminder also provides. It can be downloaded from the Geography page, which can be navigated to from a link on the main Data page.

Data Files¶

File Preparation¶

Files for each indicator were downloaded from Gapminder.org in .xlsx format, and are then converted to .csv using the my.convert_xls_to_csv function imported in this notebook. Only the sheet titled List of countries was saved to the .csv. The original files, converted files (raw) and clean .csv files are all saved in the same folder as this notebook.

Most of the original Gapminder data files contained a string with the file's title in the first cell, A1; this is replaced with the string "Country" during the conversion function before saving the .csv file.

Note: The Convert .XLS files to .CSV block below need only be run the first time in this notebook. It can be skipped on subsequent runs as the .csv files will have been created. The converted datasets can be loaded from the Load .CSV files block below.

Convert .XLS files to .CSV¶

Data Assessment¶

The datasets were assessed using some of these function calls:

df.head() | View the first 5 rows to check the data format
df.columns | Display columns, to see what years are contained
df.shape | Get the shape of the dataframe (rows, columns)
df.describe() | Display summary statistics by column
df.max(axis=1).max() | Max value in the dataset, likewise for min value; use for outliers/errors
df.info() | Description info on data types, non-nulls by column
df.isnull().sum().any() | Check to see if there are any NaNs in the dataframe, True/False
df.isnull().any(axis=1).sum() | Number of countries with NaNs
df.isnull().any().sum() | Number of years with NaNs

Data Cleaning¶

The assessment revealed that the Mean years in school datasets all begin in 1970 and have no missing data, NaNs. There were however, still many NaNs in the data after 1970 for the Life expectancy, Urban population (% of total) and GDP datasets. These incomplete dataframes were cleaned initially using 1970 as the start year, and then reexamined to see if any more years would be dropped. The GDP dataset was the first to be cleaned as it had the highest number of countries with missing data.

The my.trim_and_clean() function attempts to perform the following four actions on the dataset:

  1. The columns for years prior to that specified are dropped. In this case it is 1970.
  2. Countries that have NO data are dropped.
  3. Countries that have missing data above the set threshold of 20% (default) are dropped. Note: The reason for this is that the countries with NaNs greater than the threshold appear to either no longer exist, or have long stretches with missing data and estimates would be innappropriate guesswork.
  4. Countries with some missing data are filled (partially in some cases) using forward and back fill methods with a threshold of 3, which is the default for this exploration.

After the trim and clean, some NaNs may remain. A summary from the trim_and_clean() function, displayed in verbose mode verbose=True, shows which years and countries still contain missing data. These are then displayed in a separate cell using the 3rd function listed in the table below, to see whether the country or entire year would be dropped. For example, if only 1 country was missing data in the earliest year in the range (e.g. 1970), then this row could be manually dropped and the year kept. If several countries have missing data in the earliest years, as in the case of GDP per capita for years from 1970 to 1973, then a closer inspection may decide in favour of keeping these countries but dropping the years with missing data. There were no other scenarios played out in this exploration, however the case of missing data within years would also need close inspection to determine which approach to use.

The data cleaning used these functions:

df = my.trim_and_clean(df_raw, '1970', 20, 3) | Trim years and drop rows with missing data
df = my.trim_and_clean(df_raw, '1970', 20, 3, verbose=True) | Same, but displays detailed summary
df[df.isnull().any(axis=1)] | Display all rows that contain NaNs
df.columns[df.isnull().sum() > 0] | Display a list of columns with NaN counts
df[df['Country'] == '_name_'] | Display specified country's row
any(df['Country'] == '_name_') | Check whether country exists; True/False
df.drop(df[df['Country'] == '_name_'].index, inplace=True) | Drop specified country
df = my.trim_cols(df, ['1970', '1971', '1972', '1973']) | Drop specified years
df = my.trim_cols(df, ['1970', '1971', '1972'], verbose=True) | Same, but displays summary

Combined Datasets for 1974 and 2009 data¶

Several of the questions being explored make comparisons between the years of 1974 and 2009. Columns specific to these years from all datasets are merged to create combined separate datasets for each of these two years. A copy of the regions dataframe is used as the base for the combined dataframes.

The largest markers, in blues and greens, indicate a higher GDP per capita and are all in the upper right corner. Despite the small number of data points, what is shown here is suggestive that wealthier countries have a population with a longer Life expectancy and whose women have more years in school. It is also apparent that there are quite a few countries with a GDP in the mid-range, shown by the orange markers, who have mid to high levels of Mean years in school for women as well as Life expectancy.

Conclusions¶

The purpose of this investigation was to find out how years in school for women has changed over time, and whether any associations could be observed with other metrics, using indicators from the Gapminder.org collection for Mean years in school, Urban population, Life expectancy and GDP per capita.

Several questions were asked that looked at different aspects of the dataset for Mean years in school for women aged 25 to 34. The first, involving the Mean years in school for women by itself, simply looked at the raw data plotted for all 35 years (1974 to 2009), which showed that there has been a steady upward trend for all countries. Distribution plots for the 1974 and 2009 years reflect this trend.

Comparing the distributions of Mean years in school for men and women in the most recent year, 2009, showed that more than half of the countries had women's average years in school being more than that for men. This is very different from the same comparison made with the 1974 figures.

Grouping the data by region showed that South America as a whole had the greatest increase on average (from 1974 to 2009) compared with the other regions of the world. But looking at countries individually showed that within the top 20 countries from around the world which had the greatest increase in Mean years in school for women from 1974 to 2009, 8 of those 20 are in the Asia West region, and another 4 are from East Asia Pacific.

These top 20 countries have all seen increases of over 6.4 years, and several over 8. An attempt was made to see if there were any possible associations with the other indicators - GDP per capita, Life expectancy and Urban population - that might account for such big changes, however findings were sketchy due to the limited nature of the data.

The first scatter plot at the beginning of the EDA section showed a promising association for Life expectancy and GDP per capita with Mean years in school for women. When plotted together these three indicators produced an interesting visual, despite the amount of missing GDP data. Correlation coefficients indicated moderately high associations for both Life expectancy and on this minimal GDP data.

Overall the picture is promising, if the observed trends seen in the statistics and visuals continues. There is still room for improvement, however there are many countries and in fact all regions that have seen considerable increases in the average number of years in school for women over the 35 years of data used for this investigation.
